This is a very important andbeautiful place for the
Marquesan people, but asbeautiful as this place is,
it is steeped in a history ofviolence.
This area, in particular, washome to a legendary warrior,
Keikahanui.He was the chief of his tribe,
and he was feared among allother warriors.
His body was covered inintricate Marquesan tattoos.
Now, the tattooing processitself was very crude.
Tattoo comes were usually madefrom human bone, sometimes
pearl, and even occasionallyanimal bone.
The comb was pounded into theflesh using a mallet made of
iron wood.Very painful, took years.
Keikahanui was feared in battlebecause he always seemed to know
what his enemy was going to do,and he did this by infiltrating
the tribes of his rivals andposing as an ordinary tribesman.
Well, he was living with a rivaltribe when he learned they
planned to make war on his owntribe.
He didn't want to battle his ownpeople, so he decided to fake an
injury.He went down to the sea and he
grabbed two sea urchins.He took the guts and he wrapped
them around his foot with atapa, trying to fake an injury.
The smell was so bad the trickworked.
The rest of the rival tribethought he was incapacitated.
They went off to do war.As soon as they were out of
sight, he stripped off the twourchins, disguised himself by
taking his long hair and pullingit up into two buns and then he
grabbed his favorite weapon ofchoice, the war club, made of
iron wood, designed to kill witha blow to the head.
He knew a shortcut, took offrunning.
His plan was to ambush the warparty, kill the chief, and then
the tribe would feast on thechief.
This cannibalism was a verycommon part of Marquesan life.
It was believed that if you atethe meat of another warrior, you
inherited their power.So the fleshiest part of the
meat was reserved for thewarrior who made the kill, and
Marquesan chiefs would presideover this ceremony.

to capture their spirit.Keikahanui's plan worked
